arcoliver/statuses/19088611\">#</a></li>\n	<li>Enjoying some strawberries. Ah, springtime. <a href=\"http://twitter.com/marcoliver/statuses/19251751\">#</a></li>\n	<li>Just had dinner. More work coming up soon. <a href=\"http://twitter.com/marcoliver/statuses/19333791\">#</a></li>\n	<li>Done for today. And kind of hungry. Well, sleep might help. Good night. <a href=\"http://twitter.com/marcoliver/statuses/19464391\">#</a></li>\n</ul>','Twitter Updates for 2007-04-04','','publish','open','open','','twitter-updates-for-2007-04-04','','','2007-04-04 23:59:59','2007-04-04 23:59:59','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/twitter-updates-for-2007-04-04/',0,'post','',0),(185,1,'2007-04-05 23:59:59','2007-04-05 23:59:59','<ul>\n	<li>Alternating between coding and working in the garden. <a href=\"http://twitter.com/marcoliver/statuses/20042191\">#</a></li>\n</ul>','Twitter Updates for 2007-04-05','','publish','open','open','','twitter-updates-for-2007-04-05','','','2007-04-05 23:59:59','2007-04-05 23:59:59','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/twitter-updates-for-2007-04-05/',0,'post','',0),(186,1,'2007-04-07 13:17:07','2007-04-07 13:17:07','I had not even realized, that that Twitter summary thing was running all the time. I guess if I posted more frequently it would not look so pathetic, but that would mean I\'d have to get productive. Meh.\nIn other news, the DCiJ project is still far from being complete, but the implementation has reached a status that some people might actually call â€œalphaâ€. But there are still a lot of bugs to fix, the layout needs to be overhauled and could somebody please write me a documentation? Thanks. While you\'re at it, could you do one for Project 2 as well? Thanks, you\'re so sweet. Honestly. Like a chocolate egg. And minty fresh as well, like those After Eight ones. Yeah, just like that.\nPip-pip!','A smallish collection of BS','','publish','open','open','','a-smallish-collection-of-bs','','','2007-04-07 13:17:07','2007-04-07 13:17:07','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/a-smallish-collection-of-bs/',0,'post','',0),(187,1,'2007-04-08 07:16:17','2007-04-08 07:16:17','and a Happy New Year!\nI hope the Easter bunny brings you some nice turkeys and whatnot.','Merry Eastermas','','publish','open','open','','merry-eastermas','','','2007-04-08 07:16:17','2007-04-08 07:16:17','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/merry-eastermas/',0,'post','',0),(188,1,'2007-04-10 21:12:51','2007-04-10 21:12:51','And thus Easter break ends. Well, not the break itself, I still have a few days left, but I\'m leaving Germany tomorrow. Back to England. Only one month left until all my stuff has to be ready. WDfI is pretty much done. A&DD is virtually nonexistent as I am still waiting for Lukas to respond. DCiJ is coming along so-so, pretty much like Project 2. I really need to get more documentation done soon. And start thinking about finding work.\nTravel-day tomorrow. At least I\'ll get faster Internet access when I get there.','She packed my bags last night...','','publish','open','open','','she-packed-my-bags-last-night','','','2007-04-10 21:12:51','2007-04-10 21:12:51','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/she-packed-my-bags-last-night/',0,'post','',0),(189,1,'2007-04-12 15:24:33','2007-04-12 15:24:33','<style type=\"text/css\">\n.flickr-yourcomment { }\n.flickr-frame { text-align: left; padding: 3px; }\n.flickr-caption { font-size: 0.8em; margin-top: 0px; }\n</style>\n\n<div class=\"flickr-frame\">\n	<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/damot/456617801/\" title=\"photo sharing\"><img src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/174/456617801_b6d9aa42e7.jpg\" class=\"flickr-photo\" alt=\"\" /></a>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"flickr-yourcomment\">\n	Uploaded a handfull of shots I took on my way to and from Germany in the last couple of days. Mostly airplane wings. And clouds. And blueberries!\n</p>','PHOTOS!!!','','publish','open','open','','photos','','','2007-04-12 15:24:33','2007-04-12 15:24:33','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/photos/',0,'post','',0),(190,1,'2007-04-18 20:25:32','2007-04-18 20:25:32','Time\'s running fast. Roughly two more months before I\'m done here in Southampton. Okay, the graduation is in...November? But still, come July I better get a job somewhere.\nFinally, after 23 years of only spending money I might actually be in a situation where I can earn money as well. I will bathe in gold and diamonds. Wait, hold the diamonds. They cut.\nI guess in the coming weeks I should start to check out the job bazaars in the realm of Web and list some interesting positions. Even though I\'m probably not the â€œWeb 2.0 interaction designer with proficient skills in Actionscript and Ruby; knowledge in writing C# phone applications a must, experience with PostgreSQL based applications in BASIC optional; excellent skills in English, Latin and Hindiâ€ companies are probably looking for these days. But hey, at least I can build my own space rocket. Take that, competition!','Get a job, you punk!','','publish','open','open','','get-a-job-you-punk','','','2007-04-18 20:25:32','2007-04-18 20:25:32','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/get-a-job-you-punk/',0,'post','',0),(191,1,'2007-04-21 09:04:50','2007-04-21 09:04:50','Facing this blog\'s painfully obvious lack of content I finally decided to sit down and write a bit on each assignment I\'m currently being forced to do.\nWhy? Hell, am I supposed to know everything? Come on!\nI guess what I hope to achieve is to get a bigger picture of what I want to end up with in each of these projects. Well, we\'ll see.\nIt also keeps me from drooling over Final Cut Studio 2, wishing that I had ventured into movies instead of computers. Damn, Motion looks pretty.\nANYWAY!\nLet the magic begin!','The Assignment Chronicles: Introduction','','publish','open','open','','the-assignment-chronicles-introduction','','','2007-04-21 09:04:50','2007-04-21 09:04:50','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/the-assignment-chronicles-introduction/',0,'post','',0),(192,1,'2007-04-23 06:22:24','2007-04-23 06:22:24','Web Design for Industry, Assignment 4. Or as I call it, â€œThe Easy Oneâ€.\nThe brief for the project was a work of pure genius: â€œWrite your own brief. And make it good!â€ Awesome!\nWell, I went down to Creativityville (it\'s next to Innovationhausen, you might want to check Google Maps) and brought with me the same idea about 90% of the course had. I\'m building a  portfolio! Can I get a â€œYayâ€?\nSo I sat down and brainstormed and mind-mapped every damn idea about how I could present my person and my work. The first thing I found out is that I have even less personality than I expected. Furthermore, it\'s actually quite hard to come up with a design that represents a human vacuum.\nLuckily famous people have spent a fair share of their time in Creativityville as well, especially <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piet_Mondrian\">Mr Piet Mondrian</a>. You know, the guy who painted amazing things like â€œBlack grid. Blue square. Red square. It\'s ART!â€ Actually this is just a lame excuse to defend that my design is based on black rectangles on a white background.\nAt least I managed to shoehorn as much Javascript into it as I could possibly do without adding it just to add it. It\'s got a little Ajaxy contact form and a clicky-slidy portfolio page thingy. And everything\'s also available to those people who prefer to deactivate their Javascript and eat puppies instead. You know, Buddhists. Oh, it\'s also available in English and German.\nThe only thing I guess I will need to change once I decide to actually use the thing is add more PHP, especially to include the navigation on all pages instead of reusing the same code over and over again, since our lecturer isn\'t a big fan of languages she does not teach. Swell.\nAnyway, <a href=\"http://www.damot.org/projects/portfolio\">here you go</a>.','The Assignment Chronicles: WDfI','','publish','open','open','','the-assignment-chronicles-wdfi','','','2007-04-23 06:22:24','2007-04-23 06:22:24','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/the-assignment-chronicles-wdfi/',0,'post','',0),(193,1,'2007-04-28 06:04:50','2007-04-28 06:04:50','Next up: Project 2, or as I call it, â€œThe Big Oneâ€.\nYou know how it works, the first part is cool, the sequel is pretty much the first one again, so it is still okay but you feel a little ripped-off afterwards. Luckily there is no â€œProject 3: The Projectioningâ€.\nProject 1 was the part where I just had to dream up how the hell I was going to build the stupid application I had come up with. Project 2 is where I have to walk the walk.\nSo my amazing idea was to build a social networking site. Yeah, I know. But wait! My amazing idea was to build a social networking site. In 3D. In HTML and Javascript. Yeah, I KNOW!\nBut now allow me to ask some questions. Did you know that building a page with roughly 20 different popups can be kind of a pain? Did you know that moving 30 DIVs plus another 30 DIVs as their shadows plus another 60 invisible DIVs for additional content is actually still quite fast? Did you know that Firefox starts choking at around 100 DIVs+100 DIVs+200 DIVs? Did you know that instead of trying to run another test with 750 DIVs I could just as easily have tried to teach a rock how to dance Lambada? And did you know that adding a couple hundred more DIVs to draw lines between other DIVs can entertain a whole family in Africa for at least a year? Me neither, still there is a hint of truth in it.\nBut at least a lot of other stuff works. Actually a massive assload of stuff works. Now I just need to pull about a page of text about each of my failings out of my ass and somehow make all that amalgamate into a sweet little project report.\nOh, and then there\'s the Poster Presentation nobody is telling us anything about.\nOkay...guess I\'ll go back then. Back to my patent-pending super-cool 3D networking thingy. The one that only runs in Gecko browsers. And might work in Safari if Safari did not crash roughly 5 seconds after I logged in. Every single time.\n<a href=\"www.damot.org/koan\">Wombat!</a>','The Assignment Chronicles: Project 2','','publish','open','open','','the-assignment-chronicles-project-2','','','2007-04-28 06:04:50','2007-04-28 06:04:50','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/the-assignment-chronicles-project-2/',0,'post','',0),(194,1,'2007-04-30 05:06:50','2007-04-30 05:06:50','Be afraid, for now I give you: The DCiJ Assignment, or as I call it, â€œThe Ugly Oneâ€.\nDCiJ obviously stands for â€œDistributed Computing in Javaâ€. Didn\'t know that? No wonder you\'ve got nothing better to do than reading this blog.\nI guess the reason for this assignment must be that our lecturer fell in a coma sometime before Easter. When he woke up he had completely forgotten that he had given us workshops every week for over half a year. And that he had us do group work. And that he monitored our attendance every week. So because he has absolutely no idea how we\'ve been doing all year he gave us an assignment. Apparently the same condition overcomes him every year. He should probably have a word with his doctor.\nThe amazing task is to whip up a shop system for a car rental service. You pick your dates, you get the available cars, you pick your extras, you fill out your payment info, you book a car. Shouldn\'t be that hard, right?\nNow the fun part is that we are required to use Kodo JDO for the data storage. Wouldn\'t be that bad if it didn\'t force me to work in Windows, because apparently serious programming (Java programming, that is) can only be done in Windows. You know, not that kiddy PHP bullshit you can do on your Macintoshes and Linuxes and camera phones and what have you.\nNow, Kodo JDO is a filthy whore. Well, not really. But I\'m just completely at a loss for a description of the feeling of being raped up the ass by a moody piece of shit software. Maybe Kodo is a digital drug-addicted cross-dresser who likes to give you some though lovin\'. Yeah, close.\nIt works when it wants to, or maybe just totally at random. I bet some guy is sitting on a mountain somewhere rolling a pair of D20 to determine the use of every single instance of Kodo in the world.\nMy application is up and running by now, after I had to get some serious knife-work done on IE. If the IE team ever wanted to make their Javascript error messages any more useless they could just remove the warning sign and have the app play another of those clicking sounds whenever something is broken. Yeah, that would do. Or IE could just kick you in the balls (Assuming that only real men on real computers have the guts to do serious programming).\nOh, I need some documentation as well. If I rip out some of my teeth, maybe the tooth fairy will bring me a shitload of sequence-diagrams instead of sweet cash.','The Assignment Chronicles: DCiJ','','publish','closed','open','','the-assignment-chronicles-dcij','','','2007-04-30 05:06:50','2007-04-30 05:06:50','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/04/the-assignment-chronicles-dcij/',0,'post','',0),(195,1,'2007-05-01 05:47:21','2007-05-01 05:47:21','A little interlude of the recommendation-kind. People of Interwebland, check out Frederik\'s final year project <a href=\"http://www.magnifyarr.de/\">MAGNIFYARR</a> (formerly YARR).\nMAGNIFYARR Advanced Recommendation Repository is not only the smoking ruin of a recursive acronym but also â€œa project on personalized product recommendations. Currently MAGNIFYARR only supports books, but other products will be supported in the future. The users can specify their favourite book and rate books. Based on this data recommendations will be offered.â€\nSo as far as I understand it, you tell the system that you like a book. That\'s it. If you\'ve already liked a book before the system asks you if you liked it more or less than the last book you liked. Based on what other books people, who like the same books as you do, like you get recommendations.\nI guess. Anyway, fill the good man\'s database.','YARR','','publish','open','open','','yarr','','','2007-05-01 05:47:21','2007-05-01 05:47:21','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/05/yarr/',0,'post','',0),(196,1,'2007-05-04 14:57:04','2007-05-04 14:57:04','A&DD is history!\nLukas and I sat down for a couple of hours to put the beast together and now it\'s all done and handed in and all.\nOne down, three more to go.','The Assignment Chronicles: Interlude 1','','publish','open','open','','the-assignment-chronicles-interlude-1','','','2007-05-04 14:57:04','2007-05-04 14:57:04','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/05/the-assignment-chronicles-interlude-1/',0,'post','',0),(197,1,'2007-05-05 06:57:41','2007-05-05 06:57:41','And finally the A&DD assignment, or as I call it...well, there are no words for it really and this is growing old anyway.\nA&DD stands for â€œAdvanced and Distributed Databasesâ€. Apparently in year 2 there\'s a unit called â€œAD&Dâ€. Yet since I spent the first two years in Germany and not at SSU so many bad jokes were wasted without me even rolling a save. Oh no, he didn\'t?! Yeah, I went there!\nSo the task for the assignment is to evaluate something. More specifically, evaluate one out of four Oracle-related topics. Lukas and I picked â€œOracle and XMLâ€.\nORACLE AND XML, good or bad???\nThe job is basically to first describe what it\'s all about for a bit and then design and develop a small test application. Which was just a big bag of laughs. Our magnificent idea was to build a trigger that makes an XML-formatted summary of some other tables whenever they change, think a poor man\'s XML-based OLAP. And boy, that man sure is poor. Writing that trigger was a pain in the ass, especially when I tried to do a second one with structured storage. I wonder how people even manage to use all that crap daily with all the great documentation that is...well, not really great. The world needs an â€œOracle XML DB for Dummiesâ€-book, stat!\nOf course the application turned out to be doing only half of what we envisioned, which will at least make for a nice, angry evaluation. Oh, and the server is slow, too.\nDatabases are, like, sooo awesome!\n\nAnd it\'s already done! Yay.','The Assignment Chronicles: A&amp;DD','','publish','closed','open','','the-assignment-chronicles-add','','','2007-05-05 06:57:41','2007-05-05 06:57:41','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/05/the-assignment-chronicles-add/',0,'post','',0),(198,1,'2007-05-07 06:12:52','2007-05-07 06:12:52','And so the last week of the assignments begins.\n\nWDfI is done and waiting.\nA&DD is done and handed in.\nDCiJ is waiting to be put to paper.\nProject 2 needs to be printed and bound.\n\nLooking good.','The Assignment Chronicles: The Assignment...ing','','publish','open','open','','the-assignment-chronicles-the-assignmenting','','','2007-05-07 06:12:52','2007-05-07 06:12:52','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/05/the-assignment-chronicles-the-assignmenting/',0,'post','',0),(199,1,'2007-05-14 19:07:59','2007-05-14 19:07:59','Honestly? I have no idea why I haven\'t posted anything yet. Even though I have such great news on my hands.\nI\'m free!\nLast Wednesday I finally handed in all my remaining projects, which is to say DCiJ and Project 2. They\'re gone. Forever. Now I can travel the world and see wonders no man has ever seen.\nWell, as soon as I have gotten through those little presentations, that is. On Wednesday there is the amazing DCiJ presentation. Mark will sit down with me for fifteen minutes and will try to destroy my application, probably because he hates everything good and right in this world.\nOn the 25th of this month even greater things will happen, as this is the date of the Poster Day. On that day all of us will have to get together in a couple of rooms, produce an A2 poster out of thin air and present our Project 2 application for 15 minutes.\nOh yeah, and then there is the e-business exam. His tip for us today was â€œYou need mnemonics!â€ and â€œYou need a photographic memory to passâ€. Swell.\nIn further news, I finally have found some purpose for my <a href=\"http://marcmywords.tumblr.com/\">tumblelog</a>, which is â€œposting things that will happen to you only once in your lifeâ€. The cool thing is, I\'m only 9 days in and already running out of material.\nAnd I finally forced myself to start learning Ruby on Rails. And so far I\'m still intimidated by the shitload of functionality this thing offers, but also really impressed by the shitload of functionality this thing offers.\nOkay, that\'s all for now. I need to prepare a poster now.','Radio silence...but why, oh why?','','publish','open','open','','radio-silencebut-why-oh-why','','','2007-05-14 19:07:59','2007-05-14 19:07:59','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/05/radio-silencebut-why-oh-why/',0,'post','',0),(200,1,'2007-05-16 18:57:41','2007-05-16 18:57:41','And now the DCiJ demo is history. It went surprisingly well. Mark had me enter a couple of bookings, checked a few of the details and that was basically it. I had really imagined it to be far worse. Makes me feel a lot better about the poster day as well.\nNow I can move all the DCiJ-related files to my archive and never look at them again. At least until I need them.\nI also discovered that my voice does a really weird thing when I demo stuff to people. It gets really deep and rough. The worst thing though was when I noticed it and tried to get it a bit higher. Sounded like I was singing soprano.\nNext stop: Poster day!','Demo THIS!','','publish','open','open','','demo-this','','','2007-05-16 18:57:41','2007-05-16 18:57:41','',0,'http://www.damot.org/2007/05/demo-this/',0,'post','',0),(201,1,'2007-05-24 18:56:07','2007-05-24 18:56:07','Yay, today I finished my first little project in Ruby on Rails.\nWhat I did was simply port the CheapCarHire-site from the DCiJ assignment from Java over to RoR. I\'m pretty sure the code is pretty amateurish and it certainly was no big thing, since a lot of stuff was done in Javascript and had not to be changed at all. But it was